<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>In the loanable funds market, what happens when households become more concerned about retirement saving?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Supply shifts left, interest rates rise, quantity decreases</option>
            <option letter="b">Supply shifts right, interest rates fall, quantity increases</option>
            <option letter="c">Demand shifts left, interest rates fall, quantity decreases</option>
            <option letter="d">Demand shifts right, interest rates rise, quantity increases</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When households become more concerned about retirement, they increase their saving rate. This increases the supply of loanable funds at every interest rate (shifts the supply curve right), resulting in lower equilibrium interest rates and a larger quantity of funds being loaned in the market.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
